
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `gnome-logs` baraye didan va barrasi log-haye system dar environment GNOME be kar miravad. Ba in dastoor shoma mitoonid error-ha, warning-ha va etela'at dige ke system sabt karde ro bebinid.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `gnome-logs` --> 🖥️ Baz kardan barnameye gnome-logs ba GUI (Graphical User Interface).
    🔹 `gnome-logs --since today` --> 📅 Namayesh log-ha az emrooz be baad.
    🔹 `gnome-logs --follow` --> 🔄 Namayesh log-ha be soorate real-time (yani har chizi ezafe mishe, foran bebinid).
    🔹 `gnome-logs --level=error` --> 🚨 Namayesh log-ha faghat ba level "error".

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ gnome-logs

    🔹 Barnameye gnome-logs ro baz mikone ke shoma mitoonid log-ha ro az oonja bebinid.

    $ gnome-logs --since yesterday

    🔹 Log-ha ro az dirooz ta hala namayesh mide.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ gnome-logs --level=warning --follow

    🔹 Log-ha ro be soorate real-time faghat baraye warning-ha namayesh mide. In kheili mohemme vaghti mikhayd faqat warning-ha ro doroste koonid.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `gnome-logs` command is used to view and analyze system logs in the GNOME environment.  With this command you can inspect errors, warnings, and other information recorded by the system.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `gnome-logs` --> 🖥️ Opens the gnome-logs application with a GUI (Graphical User Interface).
    🔹 `gnome-logs --since today` --> 📅 Show logs from today onwards.
    🔹 `gnome-logs --follow` --> 🔄 Show logs in real-time (i.e., see new entries as they are added).
    🔹 `gnome-logs --level=error` --> 🚨 Show logs only with the "error" level.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ gnome-logs

    🔹 Opens the gnome-logs application where you can view logs.

    $ gnome-logs --since yesterday

    🔹 Displays logs from yesterday until now.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ gnome-logs --level=warning --follow

    🔹 Shows logs in real-time, but only for warnings.  This is very useful when you want to address warnings specifically.
